  <div class="container">
    <div class="article-page__body">
      <div class="article-page__content rte">
        <p>A well-cared-for leather jacket can easily outlast every other item in your closet — leather actually looks better with age when it's maintained correctly. The mistakes that ruin jackets early are almost always avoidable: harsh cleaners, direct heat, and long-term storage in plastic.</p>

        <h2>Everyday care</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Wipe down dust and light dirt with a soft, dry cloth after each wear.</li>
          <li>Let a wet jacket air-dry at room temperature, away from direct heat or sunlight — never use a hair dryer or radiator, which dries out and cracks the grain.</li>
          <li>Avoid overloading pockets; leather stretches under sustained weight and won't spring back.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Cleaning smooth leather</h2>
        <p>Use a cleaner made specifically for leather garments, applied with a soft cloth in small circular motions, then buffed dry. Test any product on an inconspicuous inside seam first. Skip household soaps and baby wipes — their pH and additives break down the leather's natural oils over time.</p>

        <h2>Conditioning: the step most people skip</h2>
        <p>Leather needs oil replenished every 6–12 months (more often if you wear it in dry or cold climates, which pull moisture from the hide). A quality leather conditioner restores flexibility and helps the jacket resist cracking at stress points like elbows and cuffs. Apply sparingly — a little goes further than you'd expect, and over-conditioning can leave the leather feeling greasy.</p>

        <h2>Suede is different — treat it that way</h2>
        <p>Suede has a raised nap instead of a smooth grain, so oil-based conditioners will stain it. Use a dedicated suede brush to lift dirt and restore texture, and a suede protector spray before first wear to guard against water spots.</p>

        <h2>Storage that actually protects your jacket</h2>
        <ol>
          <li>Use a wide, padded hanger — wire hangers create shoulder dimples that are hard to reverse.</li>
          <li>Store in a breathable garment bag (cotton, not plastic) so the leather can still exchange air.</li>
          <li>Keep it in a cool, dry closet away from direct sunlight, which fades and dries leather over time.</li>
          <li>Never fold a leather jacket for long-term storage — creases can become permanent.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2>When to call a professional</h2>
        <p>Deep stains, color fading, or a torn lining are best handled by a leather specialist rather than a home fix — a bad DIY repair is often more visible (and more expensive to correct) than the original damage.</p>

